Now back to the show.

61
00:03:15,360 --> 00:03:19,340
Kevin Knuth, this is an absolute honor, and it's been a long time coming.

62
00:03:20,020 --> 00:03:25,040
You're a physicist at the University of Albany, and to me, you are one of the few people who

63
00:03:25,040 --> 00:03:28,740
speaks about UFOs in a really concrete, hard-headed way.

64
00:03:28,820 --> 00:03:34,140
I think you're one of the few people I know who are studying how these crafts actually fly,

65
00:03:34,520 --> 00:03:38,120
how to detect them, and so I'm really excited to have you.

66
00:03:38,200 --> 00:03:38,460
Thank you.

67
00:03:38,500 --> 00:03:40,240
Wow, and thank you so much for having me.

68
00:03:40,380 --> 00:03:41,180
It's very exciting.

69
00:03:41,480 --> 00:03:42,760
Oh, no, it's an absolute honor.

70
00:03:42,760 --> 00:03:45,900
And you have a NASA background as well.

71
00:03:46,320 --> 00:03:52,520
I want to know how you got into UFOs to begin with, because a lot of people with your sort

72
00:03:52,520 --> 00:03:55,540
of credentials and background think UFOs are a joke.

73
00:03:56,980 --> 00:03:57,800
Right, yeah.

74
00:03:57,920 --> 00:04:01,200
I mean, I've always been interested in UFOs.

75
00:04:01,500 --> 00:04:05,460
I was 12 when Star Wars came out in 1977.

76
00:04:05,460 --> 00:04:10,180
And during that time, I mean, it was the same year Close Encounters, The Third Kind came out.

77
00:04:10,620 --> 00:04:16,360
It was, you know, another movie studio's response to Star Wars that came out in December.

78
00:04:16,440 --> 00:04:20,900
And I didn't like it as much, because there weren't spaceships shooting each other with lasers, right?

79
00:04:20,900 --> 00:04:24,020
You know, so as a 12-year-old, that wasn't that exciting.

80
00:04:24,720 --> 00:04:30,940
But at the same time, you know, there were TV shows like In Search Of with Leonard Nimoy,

81
00:04:31,360 --> 00:04:33,420
and they would cover UFO topics.

82
00:04:33,520 --> 00:04:36,460
And that was on every night, like at 6.30 when we're eating dinner.

83
00:04:36,640 --> 00:04:38,280
So I watched that all the time.

84
00:04:38,280 --> 00:04:40,500
So I've always been interested in them.

85
00:04:41,020 --> 00:04:49,780
And I think I wasn't, so I went to graduate school in 1988.

86
00:04:50,500 --> 00:04:55,820
I grew up in Wisconsin, and I moved out to Montana to go to graduate school at Montana State University

87
00:04:55,820 --> 00:04:56,320
in Bozeman.

88
00:04:57,100 --> 00:05:05,220
And our first week or two there, I had just moved there, and there was a cattle mutilation

89
00:05:05,220 --> 00:05:10,020
where two cows were killed and surgically manipulated.

90
00:05:10,300 --> 00:05:12,500
I don't have a good word for what happened to them.

91
00:05:13,140 --> 00:05:14,300
The blood was drained.

92
00:05:14,620 --> 00:05:15,540
The blood was drained.

93
00:05:15,840 --> 00:05:18,380
The sensory organs removed.

94
00:05:18,520 --> 00:05:19,500
The genitals removed.

95
00:05:20,040 --> 00:05:22,040
One of them had like a core sample.

96
00:05:22,160 --> 00:05:24,480
It had this cylindrical hole punched through it.

97
00:05:24,980 --> 00:05:26,020
Just bizarre.

98
00:05:26,200 --> 00:05:26,900
I mean, really bizarre.

99
00:05:27,580 --> 00:05:31,060
And the people on the news were crazed about this, right?

100
00:05:31,100 --> 00:05:33,720
Oh, my God, there's, you know, these two cows on this ranch were killed.

101
00:05:33,720 --> 00:05:38,460
And there were UFO reports in the county that night, hundreds of reports.

102
00:05:38,820 --> 00:05:43,000
And so the two stories were that it was either aliens or Satanists.

103
00:05:43,600 --> 00:05:46,940
And everybody's all got their undies in a bundle over this, right?

104
00:05:47,100 --> 00:05:52,920
And so we're at the physics department, and some of us grad students are talking about this.

105
00:05:53,500 --> 00:05:58,060
And especially the new graduate students, we've all just moved there into a PhD program.

106
00:05:58,160 --> 00:06:02,260
So you're looking down the barrel of spending five or six years of your life at this place.

107
00:06:02,260 --> 00:06:11,480
And what kind of place did we just move to where cows are murdered this way, right?

108
00:06:11,740 --> 00:06:12,520
This is really bizarre.

109
00:06:12,680 --> 00:06:16,720
So we're discussing this in the hallway, and it was this heated discussion.

110
00:06:17,200 --> 00:06:24,760
And I remember shouting at one point, I don't know why aliens would do it, and I don't know how Satanists would do it.

111
00:06:24,760 --> 00:06:28,760
I mean, it was that level of stupid discussion, right, that students would have.

112
00:06:29,160 --> 00:06:35,880
And we were quite loud and disturbed one of the professors down the hall, and he came out from his office to find out what we're talking about.

113
00:06:35,920 --> 00:06:38,020
He comes down the hall, and we tell him.

114
00:06:38,160 --> 00:06:45,340
And I don't know if he was trying to make us feel better because it was the opposite, but he said, oh, yeah, yeah, this happens from time to time.

115
00:06:45,340 --> 00:06:51,140
And they'll investigate it, and they won't figure anything out, and then everybody will just forget about it until it happens again.

116
00:06:52,140 --> 00:06:53,920
And we're just like, what?

117
00:06:54,040 --> 00:06:58,520
That's even crazier than what we're already talking about.

118
00:06:58,960 --> 00:07:02,000
And then he adds, and he goes, but you know what's really strange?

119
00:07:02,700 --> 00:07:12,480
There are, he goes, I have friends who work up at Malmstrom Air Force Base, and they have problems with UFOs flying over the nuclear missile sites and shutting down nuclear missiles.

120
00:07:12,480 --> 00:07:22,640
And, you know, we listened politely, and when he walked away, we laughed our asses off because this was the, at the time, it was the silliest thing I thought I'd ever heard.

121
00:07:22,780 --> 00:07:29,360
I mean, UFOs are shutting down nuclear missiles, and this isn't, everybody's not on red alert.

122
00:07:29,700 --> 00:07:35,020
I mean, our entire military should be mobilized or something like that, right?

123
00:07:35,380 --> 00:07:36,920
So we just didn't believe it.

124
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:38,120
We thought this was just silly.

125
00:07:38,520 --> 00:07:40,180
And it became kind of a running joke.

126
00:07:40,180 --> 00:07:47,820
Like, anytime something weird would happen at, you know, at school or somebody's telling a story, oh, this weird thing happened to me, someone would invariably interject.

127
00:07:48,160 --> 00:07:49,280
But you know what's really strange?

128
00:07:49,520 --> 00:07:53,720
UFOs are shutting down nuclear missiles up in Malmstrom Air Force Base, and we would all laugh, right?

129
00:07:54,220 --> 00:07:56,620
And so that was a running joke for a whole year.

130
00:07:57,380 --> 00:08:01,580
And so now time passes, and that was September of 1988.

131
00:08:02,760 --> 00:08:05,560
And he had said that it was ongoing.

132
00:08:05,760 --> 00:08:08,460
He said they are doing this presently, right?

133
00:08:08,460 --> 00:08:17,260
And so now fast forward to, it was about 2015, so it's a couple years before the New York Times article.

134
00:08:18,120 --> 00:08:26,460
And I was teaching an astronomy class, and we got to the point where we were talking about the possibility of life elsewhere.

135
00:08:26,960 --> 00:08:29,620
And some of the students wanted me to comment on UFOs.

136
00:08:29,820 --> 00:08:33,160
I'm like, well, I don't know anything about UFOs, and it's certainly not science.

137
00:08:33,160 --> 00:08:36,980
This is an astronomy class, so I was just poking around on the Internet.

138
00:08:37,140 --> 00:08:43,180
Is there anything reasonable I can actually say other than the Drake equation and the Fermi paradox, right?

139
00:08:43,220 --> 00:08:45,760
The two typical things that scientists might talk about.

140
00:08:45,760 --> 00:09:00,600
And I was just poking around at like 2 a.m., and I stumbled on Robert Hastings' news conference from like 2010, where he had six people on from the Air Force, various Air Force positions.

141
00:09:01,200 --> 00:09:08,060
The first one was Robert Salas talking about UFOs shutting down nuclear missiles at Malmstrom Air Force Base.

142
00:09:08,060 --> 00:09:13,760
And I was like, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, I heard about this in grad school, that was a joke, right?

143
00:09:14,100 --> 00:09:17,860
And then I'm listening to this, I'm like, that's just not a joke.

144
00:09:18,080 --> 00:09:29,160
Between September of 66 and March of 67, we lost 30 missiles to UFO activity.

145
00:09:29,380 --> 00:09:30,880
It's wild, yeah.

146
00:09:31,160 --> 00:09:31,560
30.

147
00:09:32,020 --> 00:09:32,440
30.

148
00:09:32,660 --> 00:09:34,280
That's pretty insane.

149
00:09:34,280 --> 00:09:36,200
Now, now what are you doing?

150
00:09:36,200 --> 00:09:38,560
He's talking about events from 1966.

151
00:09:40,120 --> 00:09:42,100
And I heard about it in 1988.

152
00:09:42,600 --> 00:09:47,200
And the professor that told me in 1988 about this said that it is happening.

153
00:09:47,980 --> 00:09:55,420
So this has been going on for 20 years, and no one's paying any attention to this.

154
00:09:56,120 --> 00:10:01,260
I mean, the Army's still not, the military's still not mobilized and worrying about this.

155
00:10:01,260 --> 00:10:05,000
And I thought, there is something really wrong here.

156
00:10:05,960 --> 00:10:09,000
And I spent some time thinking about it.

157
00:10:09,040 --> 00:10:12,160
I was up late that night teaching class early, right?

158
00:10:12,180 --> 00:10:13,100
I didn't barely sleep.

159
00:10:13,460 --> 00:10:24,800
But I'm thinking about it, and I thought, I mean, it's either nonsense, and the people who are in charge of our nuclear missiles are people we shouldn't be trusting with anything.

160
00:10:24,800 --> 00:10:34,160
Or this is actually real, which makes more sense considering the amount of time that's involved, a 20-year time span.

161
00:10:35,040 --> 00:10:39,660
And nobody's reacting to it, maybe because they all think it's nonsense.

162
00:10:39,780 --> 00:10:41,380
And I thought, this is extremely dangerous.

163
00:10:41,780 --> 00:10:44,920
We're going to get blindsided by something if we're not careful.

164
00:10:44,920 --> 00:10:48,080
And I thought, somebody ought to look into this.

165
00:10:48,140 --> 00:10:50,620
And I thought, I'm going to start looking into this UFO business.

166
00:10:50,780 --> 00:10:52,040
What is here?

167
00:10:52,120 --> 00:10:52,920
How real is this?

168
00:10:52,980 --> 00:10:53,860
How possible is this?

169
00:10:53,960 --> 00:10:56,080
And so that's when I started looking into it.

170
00:10:57,380 --> 00:11:05,400
And I had actually given a talk in our department like a year later after I looked into it somewhat.

171
00:11:05,520 --> 00:11:07,140
I thought, this is actually really interesting.

172
00:11:07,140 --> 00:11:14,360
So I gave a talk in our physics department about it, just an informal talk, and the room was packed.

173
00:11:14,720 --> 00:11:21,340
I mean, I don't know how many people can actually sit in that room, but it was well over the fire limit, right?

174
00:11:21,540 --> 00:11:24,580
I mean, we had people sitting cross-legged right up to the front screen.

175
00:11:25,680 --> 00:11:27,880
And the talk went on.

176
00:11:28,040 --> 00:11:28,940
There were so many questions.

177
00:11:29,020 --> 00:11:30,600
I talked for it for almost three hours.

178
00:11:31,220 --> 00:11:34,620
And most people just stayed for it because everybody was really interested.

179
00:11:34,620 --> 00:11:36,860
And I thought, yeah, see, this is interesting.

180
00:11:36,860 --> 00:11:38,860
I mean, this is an interesting problem here.

181
00:11:39,060 --> 00:11:40,460
And it's not that simple.

182
00:11:41,400 --> 00:11:45,760
And then, of course, a year after that, the New York Times article comes out.

183
00:11:46,460 --> 00:11:50,200
And I thought, well, somebody ought to study this.

184
00:11:50,300 --> 00:11:52,460
And I thought, well, shoot, you just do it.

185
00:11:52,960 --> 00:11:53,560
I should do it.

186
00:11:53,940 --> 00:11:59,220
And the nuclear link, I could see that being the perfect gateway for rigorous scientists like yourself.

187
00:11:59,320 --> 00:12:03,340
Because I think science in the conventional sense has to be repeatable.

188
00:12:03,340 --> 00:12:09,100
You know, every time you drop this pen, it needs to fall in sort of the same way for it to be science.

189
00:12:09,820 --> 00:12:20,320
And so I think the nuclear link is a version of that with UFOs where UFOs seem to show up across nuclear bases, not only in the U.S., but all over the world.

190
00:12:20,760 --> 00:12:22,440
And that's one thing that worried me.

191
00:12:22,520 --> 00:12:25,920
Once I looked into it, I thought, wow, this is happening in the Soviet Union.

192
00:12:26,020 --> 00:12:27,160
This is happening in France.

193
00:12:27,160 --> 00:12:28,220
This is happening in England.

194
00:12:28,220 --> 00:12:29,780
We were talking before the show.

195
00:12:29,900 --> 00:12:40,460
I'm wearing my American Alchemy Japan shirt, which is paying homage to Lino, which is a town next to their Fukushima prefecture, where they have – they're famous for their nuclear spill in 2011.

196
00:12:40,600 --> 00:12:42,000
They have their civilian energy grid.

197
00:12:42,540 --> 00:12:44,500
And UFOs were reported to show up there.

198
00:12:44,600 --> 00:12:46,220
They have a whole museum dedicated to UFOs.

199
00:12:46,940 --> 00:12:47,120
Right.

200
00:12:47,120 --> 00:12:53,780
And Vice did a documentary on them in 2022, and it's the town in Japan that's obsessed with UFOs, and it's right next to this nuclear grid.

201
00:12:53,780 --> 00:12:58,900
And then I think there was a Netflix Encounter episode, I think episode four, focused on that as well.

202
00:12:59,060 --> 00:13:03,700
And Malmstrom, where you mentioned, that is the site of tons and tons of activity.

203
00:13:03,860 --> 00:13:06,820
You have Bob Salas, obviously, in 67.

204
00:13:07,620 --> 00:13:10,120
But before that, you had this Echo Flight incident.

205
00:13:10,520 --> 00:13:10,620
Right.

206
00:13:10,620 --> 00:13:14,320
You know, I think it was like very – I think it was 10 days before or something.

207
00:13:14,420 --> 00:13:15,480
One was March 16th.

208
00:13:15,480 --> 00:13:16,640
One was March 24th.

209
00:13:17,320 --> 00:13:22,900
Then you have John Mills, this retired missile technician in the early 90s, seeing a bunch of UFOs there.

210
00:13:23,280 --> 00:13:27,360
You even have an interview with this guy, Chris Langan, which – say what you will about the guy.

211
00:13:27,500 --> 00:13:29,240
He says he has the highest IQ in the world.

212
00:13:29,320 --> 00:13:30,480
He seems a little cocky to me.

213
00:13:30,680 --> 00:13:32,080
But he's just offhand.

214
00:13:32,240 --> 00:13:37,020
He's saying he's seen UFOs, and he's seen them around Malmstrom Air Force Base.

215
00:13:37,020 --> 00:13:42,120
On the UFO thing, I was working for the Forest Service, not too far from Malmstrom Air Force Base.

216
00:13:42,460 --> 00:13:47,040
One day, I was up there in a Forest Service pickup truck at a certain campground.

217
00:13:47,400 --> 00:13:52,340
And I was there, and suddenly, I look up, and I say suddenly.

218
00:13:52,460 --> 00:13:53,500
It was just in the skies.

219
00:13:53,800 --> 00:13:56,420
I became aware that it was up there, and I looked up.

220
00:13:56,780 --> 00:14:05,700
There's this huge, spheroidal, you know, but elliptical, not a perfect spheroid, like a saucer that was turned partially on its side.

221
00:14:05,940 --> 00:14:06,140
Right.

222
00:14:06,140 --> 00:14:10,560
And so it's just this recurring trope from all these uncorrelated sources.

223
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:19,700
Robert Hastings, who wrote the book, UFOs and Nukes, got into this whole subject because his father was actually working at Malmstrom Base.

224
00:14:20,140 --> 00:14:26,540
And he was learning radar theory from one of the radar operators there, Bob Hastings, was while he was a janitor.

225
00:14:26,640 --> 00:14:27,420
He was in high school.

226
00:14:27,840 --> 00:14:31,320
And the radar operator was like, we're tracking some of these unknowns.

227
00:14:31,480 --> 00:14:32,620
You should take a look.

228
00:14:32,620 --> 00:14:34,140
And then that was it for him.

229
00:14:34,180 --> 00:14:37,040
He was hooked, and he dedicated his life to studying this stuff.

230
00:14:37,040 --> 00:14:37,900
That's amazing, yeah.

231
00:14:37,940 --> 00:14:38,940
So, yeah.

232
00:14:39,080 --> 00:14:39,760
Yeah, it's cool.

233
00:14:39,960 --> 00:14:41,780
It was maybe three years ago.

234
00:14:41,780 --> 00:14:46,660
We were down in Louisiana visiting my in-laws for Mardi Gras.

235
00:14:47,200 --> 00:14:51,240
And so it was February, and we're outside grilling, right?

236
00:14:51,640 --> 00:14:58,020
And I was grilling with my wife's Uncle Matt, and he had his Air Force cap on.

237
00:14:58,020 --> 00:15:02,480
And I spotted Malmstrom Air Force Base on his Air Force cap.

238
00:15:02,540 --> 00:15:07,300
And I was like, Uncle Matt, you were in the Air Force, and you were at Malmstrom.

239
00:15:07,580 --> 00:15:08,400
You were at Malmstrom?

240
00:15:08,680 --> 00:15:10,700
And he goes, yeah, I was stationed in Malmstrom.

241
00:15:10,880 --> 00:15:11,780
I go, when were you there?

242
00:15:11,800 --> 00:15:17,360
And he goes, oh, like 1971 through 74, something like that, and early 70s.

243
00:15:17,480 --> 00:15:22,680
And I said, did you ever hear anything about UFO incursions at nuclear weapon sites?

244
00:15:22,720 --> 00:15:24,860
He goes, oh, that happened all the time.

245
00:15:25,020 --> 00:15:27,120
These things would come in and shut down the nuclear weapons.

246
00:15:27,120 --> 00:15:28,640
And he was going on and on about this.

247
00:15:28,740 --> 00:15:31,300
And I'm like, it's common knowledge, right?

248
00:15:31,860 --> 00:15:35,760
And how is it Congress is just finding out about this, right?

249
00:15:35,920 --> 00:15:40,680
And my wife's Uncle Matt has known this since 1971.

250
00:15:41,380 --> 00:15:43,020
This is something to worry about, right?

251
00:15:43,220 --> 00:15:44,360
And I was so excited.

252
00:15:44,540 --> 00:15:50,280
I told him, okay, can you tell my wife this because I'm tired of being the only crazy person in the world?

253
00:15:52,560 --> 00:15:54,700
But his response was amazing.

254
00:15:54,820 --> 00:15:56,260
Oh, yeah, this happened all the time.

255
00:15:56,260 --> 00:15:58,440
And, like, it's nothing, right?

256
00:15:58,440 --> 00:16:10,680
So, on the one hand, you have UFOs showing up around our most important assets or nuclear assets with people who are on the PRP program who literally, like, they have to report if they're on ibuprofen.

257
00:16:10,880 --> 00:16:12,500
These are people who work at the nuclear bases.

258
00:16:12,660 --> 00:16:15,440
So, they're the picture of mental health and of sound mind.

259
00:16:15,440 --> 00:16:20,020
And they all see tic-tacs, saucers, orbs, you know, shutting down nukes.

260
00:16:20,400 --> 00:16:20,420
Right.

261
00:16:20,860 --> 00:16:21,500
There's that.

262
00:16:21,600 --> 00:16:26,160
And then there's the idea that the U.S. government might have saucers and hangers.

263
00:16:26,460 --> 00:16:26,700
Right.

264
00:16:27,060 --> 00:16:30,280
Do you think – it's clear that this is happening, the nuclear thing.

265
00:16:30,320 --> 00:16:30,680
Yeah, yeah.

266
00:16:30,680 --> 00:16:31,120
That's clear.

267
00:16:31,180 --> 00:16:31,940
Absolutely clear, yeah.

268
00:16:31,940 --> 00:16:41,000
Do you think the U.S. government has saucers and hangers and we have an active reverse engineering program for nuts and bolts physical craft?

269
00:16:41,340 --> 00:16:42,400
I think that's probably true.

270
00:16:42,580 --> 00:16:46,840
I've heard this from enough people who've done that kind of work for years now.

271
00:16:47,000 --> 00:16:48,960
That's probably the case, yeah.

272
00:16:49,040 --> 00:16:51,400
Have you met anybody working on the crafts themselves?

273
00:16:51,760 --> 00:16:54,460
I've met people who've claimed to have worked on them or seen them.

274
00:16:54,540 --> 00:16:54,800
Really?

275
00:16:54,940 --> 00:16:55,360
So, yeah.

276
00:16:55,720 --> 00:16:57,660
Anybody that you can mention or –

277
00:16:57,660 --> 00:16:58,760
No, I shouldn't do that.

278
00:16:58,820 --> 00:16:59,120
Okay.

279
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:02,980
These are whispers that you get every now and again, right?

280
00:17:03,000 --> 00:17:04,520
Did you find them believable, though?

281
00:17:04,540 --> 00:17:05,840
Yeah, entirely believable, yeah.

282
00:17:05,840 --> 00:17:06,140
Really?

283
00:17:06,260 --> 00:17:06,400
Yeah.

284
00:17:06,680 --> 00:17:08,760
No, you didn't sense any sort of deception?

285
00:17:09,160 --> 00:17:09,880
No, no.

286
00:17:10,320 --> 00:17:13,680
One of the most believable things I've heard is, well, have you been able to figure anything out?

287
00:17:13,820 --> 00:17:16,440
No, we don't know what anything is or how anything works.

288
00:17:16,640 --> 00:17:16,980
Yes.

289
00:17:17,060 --> 00:17:19,380
That was my most – and I was like, all right, that makes sense.

290
00:17:19,900 --> 00:17:20,300
Interesting.

291
00:17:20,760 --> 00:17:20,940
Yeah.

292
00:17:20,940 --> 00:17:26,380
So, it's like, you know, giving an iPhone to a caveman or something.

293
00:17:26,560 --> 00:17:27,600
Something like that, yeah.

294
00:17:27,760 --> 00:17:28,160
Interesting.

295
00:17:28,280 --> 00:17:34,520
I mean, it seems like any technologies they've got from it are just, you know, surface level type stuff.

296
00:17:34,620 --> 00:17:35,980
Oh, this is some interesting material.

297
00:17:36,080 --> 00:17:36,740
What's it made of?

298
00:17:36,960 --> 00:17:38,040
That level.

299
00:17:38,920 --> 00:17:43,520
If I were on the inside, I would probably want somebody like you working on this sort of thing.

300
00:17:43,600 --> 00:17:46,460
I would love to be working on this, but not black work.

301
00:17:46,540 --> 00:17:47,820
I'd love to work on this in the open.

302
00:17:47,960 --> 00:17:48,220
Okay.

303
00:17:48,220 --> 00:17:50,600
Have you ever been contacted to do black work?

304
00:17:51,520 --> 00:17:55,440
I had the opportunity to have clearance when I worked at NASA.

305
00:17:55,640 --> 00:17:55,860
Okay.

306
00:17:55,940 --> 00:17:57,120
But I turned it down.

307
00:17:57,840 --> 00:18:00,100
Because you've always wanted to do things in an open, transparent way.

308
00:18:00,100 --> 00:18:08,920
Yeah, I'm a scientist, and I want to – and one of the benefits of being a scientist is we share information, we work together, we cooperate.

309
00:18:09,460 --> 00:18:09,840
Do you think that's –

310
00:18:09,840 --> 00:18:14,700
And, yeah, there's some competition, but there's a lot of collaboration as well, so – and that's very healthy.

311
00:18:14,700 --> 00:18:18,800
Do you think that's part of what's held back, the legacy UFO program?

312
00:18:19,320 --> 00:18:30,780
If it's held back at all, it's because you've got 10 people closeted working on one thing, and they don't get extra information that you might need to get interesting ideas.

313
00:18:30,780 --> 00:18:36,080
You know, the more people you have working on a problem, the more diversity of ideas you're going to get.

314
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:47,040
Do you think that there are certain scientific things that you can't work on in the kind of civil side, you know, open world of science without receiving backlash?

315
00:18:48,540 --> 00:18:49,580
UFOs is one of them.

316
00:18:49,780 --> 00:18:49,940
Yeah.

317
00:18:49,940 --> 00:18:55,920
Yeah, we – there was some backlash – some backlash when we started working on UFOs.

318
00:18:56,240 --> 00:18:56,800
It was –

319
00:18:56,800 --> 00:19:03,320
You mentioned on Danny Jones that you've had various friends work on anti-gravity and receive sort of backlash.

320
00:19:03,940 --> 00:19:05,980
Threatened threats and things like that, yeah, too.

321
00:19:06,120 --> 00:19:06,800
That's scary.

322
00:19:07,200 --> 00:19:08,420
That's very strange, yeah.

323
00:19:08,620 --> 00:19:11,060
What do you think that is with the anti-gravity stuff?

324
00:19:11,060 --> 00:19:13,220
I really have no idea.

325
00:19:13,380 --> 00:19:21,720
I mean, I – you know, you can jump to conclusions and say, well, because somebody doesn't want other people discovering things that they know about and have control over.

326
00:19:21,840 --> 00:19:26,500
I mean, you could jump to that conclusion, but I don't – I don't actually know what the situation is.

327
00:19:26,560 --> 00:19:27,260
It's hard to tell.

328
00:19:27,600 --> 00:19:29,500
Doesn't that feel like the base case conclusion?

329
00:19:29,500 --> 00:19:41,980
Like, if somebody's getting threatened over discovering a thing, it would seem like there'd be some group on the inside that would be tracking people trying to discover a thing that they're already aware of, right?

330
00:19:42,020 --> 00:19:42,260
Yeah, exactly.

331
00:19:42,340 --> 00:19:44,700
Like, that seems like the Occam's razor easy explanation.

332
00:19:44,720 --> 00:19:47,900
Yeah, I mean, it leads to a whole sets of conspiracy theories, right?

333
00:19:47,980 --> 00:19:48,960
And it's difficult.

334
00:19:49,580 --> 00:19:49,900
Yeah.

335
00:19:50,520 --> 00:19:54,780
Yeah, I've done deep dives on this guy like Townsend Brown, who I'm really fascinated with.

336
00:19:54,780 --> 00:19:58,640
And I talk about him probably too much, but the audience always laughs when I talk.

337
00:19:58,860 --> 00:20:08,820
But, you know, I find him to be really interesting because I do think he made breakthroughs in the world of gravity, this sort of Byfield-Brown effect, which is, I think, a very simple experiment.

338
00:20:09,140 --> 00:20:10,700
But have you looked into that at all?

339
00:20:10,900 --> 00:20:13,560
I haven't looked into that much at all.

340
00:20:14,820 --> 00:20:15,940
You have limited time.

341
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:16,580
That's the problem.

342
00:20:16,720 --> 00:20:19,760
I've got stacks of books I want to read and things I want to look at.

343
00:20:19,920 --> 00:20:20,140
Yeah.

344
00:20:20,140 --> 00:20:22,340
It's just – you have to pick and choose.

345
00:20:22,340 --> 00:20:35,920
And I think that's one reason why you don't have academics in the past looking into UFOs, because why spend time on something that's probably nonsensical when you can be spending time on something that is probably going to pay off?

346
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:38,540
And I think that's the calculation most people are doing.

347
00:20:39,600 --> 00:20:42,040
Except at this point, I don't think it's nonsensical.

348
00:20:42,260 --> 00:20:44,240
So, the payoff's huge, right?

349
00:20:44,880 --> 00:20:47,160
How do you think UFOs fly?

350
00:20:48,040 --> 00:20:49,360
I have no idea.

351
00:20:49,360 --> 00:20:53,100
They're very strange in a lot of ways.

352
00:20:53,280 --> 00:20:57,460
First, the – how many ways are they strange, right?

353
00:20:59,940 --> 00:21:04,620
The speeds and accelerations are crazy, right?

354
00:21:04,740 --> 00:21:07,180
The accelerations, nobody's going to survive that.

355
00:21:07,520 --> 00:21:10,840
So, the equipment isn't going to survive it.

356
00:21:10,840 --> 00:21:22,420
So, you know, in the Nimitz case, we estimated the acceleration of the Tic Tac dropping from 28,000 feet to sea level in 0.75 seconds or so, 0.78 seconds.

357
00:21:23,580 --> 00:21:26,920
It's about 5,000 Gs of acceleration minimum, right?

358
00:21:27,620 --> 00:21:29,760
5,000 Gs is insane.

359
00:21:29,760 --> 00:21:35,980
The new F-35 fighter jets, their wings rip off at 13 Gs.

360
00:21:36,600 --> 00:21:44,900
You know, most missile frames can't handle more than – a missile can't maneuver at more than about 35 Gs.

361
00:21:44,980 --> 00:21:48,500
And the frame isn't going to survive more than 60 Gs.

362
00:21:48,500 --> 00:21:52,220
And now you've got this Tic Tac thing accelerating at 5,000 Gs.

363
00:21:52,340 --> 00:21:53,380
That's not possible.

364
00:21:53,800 --> 00:21:55,260
I mean, equipment won't survive.

365
00:21:55,680 --> 00:22:01,880
So, now this leads you to think the only solution there is you've got to be playing with inertia somehow.

366
00:22:02,120 --> 00:22:03,860
You've got to be playing with gravity somehow.

367
00:22:04,460 --> 00:22:10,720
And so, that leads you down the path of general relativity and warp drive and that way of thinking, right?

368
00:22:10,720 --> 00:22:16,080
Do you have, like, a propulsion modality that you like best when it comes to UFOs?

369
00:22:16,100 --> 00:22:17,180
No, I don't exactly.

370
00:22:17,540 --> 00:22:19,480
But then the other problem is power.

371
00:22:19,660 --> 00:22:28,520
If you look at energies and power involved, the amount of power for that Tic Tac dropping is something like – what was it?

372
00:22:28,560 --> 00:22:30,500
It was 1,100 gigawatts of power.

373
00:22:31,780 --> 00:22:37,060
You know, I remember Back to the Future with Doc Brown, 2.1 gigawatts.

374
00:22:37,100 --> 00:22:38,180
Like, that's crazy or something.

375
00:22:38,180 --> 00:22:40,800
This thing was 1,100 gigawatts, right?

376
00:22:40,920 --> 00:22:41,860
I mean, this is –

377
00:22:41,860 --> 00:22:45,360
And he had Mr. Fusion, which was a nuclear fusion machine.

378
00:22:45,860 --> 00:22:46,440
That's right.

379
00:22:47,040 --> 00:22:47,220
Yeah.

380
00:22:47,320 --> 00:22:53,780
So, this is more power – the Tic Tac maneuver took more power than the total nuclear power output of the United States.

381
00:22:54,240 --> 00:22:54,640
Wow.

382
00:22:55,220 --> 00:22:55,460
Wow.

383
00:22:55,480 --> 00:22:58,120
And that's in that Tic Tac in the size of an F-18.

384
00:22:58,280 --> 00:22:59,180
I mean, that's crazy.

385
00:22:59,900 --> 00:23:03,860
And so, now how do you get your head around that?

386
00:23:04,860 --> 00:23:08,100
So, let's say they can deal with that kind of power.

387
00:23:08,240 --> 00:23:11,360
For some reason, they have access to that much energy.

388
00:23:13,520 --> 00:23:15,720
Equipment is never 100% efficient.

389
00:23:16,760 --> 00:23:18,940
So, a 1% inefficiency.

390
00:23:19,440 --> 00:23:24,080
So, most of the things we make are like 20% efficient at best, right?

391
00:23:25,080 --> 00:23:26,620
So, let's say they're really good at this.

392
00:23:26,660 --> 00:23:28,620
They can get to 99% efficiency.

393
00:23:28,860 --> 00:23:31,300
That means you've got a 1% inefficiency.

394
00:23:31,880 --> 00:23:38,100
1% of 1,000 gigawatts is like 11 gigawatts of power.

395
00:23:39,060 --> 00:23:42,420
That means 11 gigawatts of power is going into waste heat.

396
00:23:42,420 --> 00:23:44,520
The thing would melt.

397
00:23:45,800 --> 00:23:46,920
So, now what's happening?

398
00:23:47,100 --> 00:23:49,680
Are they really more efficient than 99%?

399
00:23:50,780 --> 00:23:53,900
Or do we have something wrong?

400
00:23:54,140 --> 00:23:55,840
Are we looking at this the wrong way maybe?

401
00:23:55,940 --> 00:23:59,820
Maybe they're not actually moving in such a way that takes that much power.

402
00:23:59,980 --> 00:24:00,700
Do you have any theories?

403
00:24:00,700 --> 00:24:02,800
I don't exactly.

404
00:24:03,580 --> 00:24:05,680
Warp drive is certainly on the table.

405
00:24:05,680 --> 00:24:22,920
But that too is messy because we don't know enough about how, you know, since there has been theoretical work done on warp bubbles, we don't really know how these would interact with matter.

406
00:24:23,620 --> 00:24:26,800
So, what does a warp bubble do in an atmosphere?

407
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:29,280
We don't, nobody's, I don't think, has looked into that.

408
00:24:29,280 --> 00:24:33,800
So, these things are strange because they don't appear to be interacting with the atmosphere at all.

409
00:24:33,800 --> 00:24:38,460
There's no sonic boom, there's no fireball, there's no sound in many cases.

410
00:24:38,980 --> 00:24:44,540
The underwater UFOs, you've even got more, and you should be able to have much more friction there.

411
00:24:44,920 --> 00:24:45,860
These things are moving.

412
00:24:45,860 --> 00:25:03,520
The one with the New Zealand frigate in the 1980s, the HMNZS Southland, had an 800-foot-long USO following it, and it was about two kilometers behind the ship.

413
00:25:03,520 --> 00:25:10,240
And actually closed that distance in 25 seconds and went under the ship and drained all the batteries, drained all the power from the ship.

414
00:25:11,160 --> 00:25:20,040
And you've got to clear, the width of this thing was about 150 feet in diameter, this cylindrical-shaped object, 800 feet long.

415
00:25:20,240 --> 00:25:21,860
So, it's, so it's, what is that?

416
00:25:21,860 --> 00:25:28,040
That's 30% longer than the largest Russian sub, which would be the Typhoon-class subs, right?

417
00:25:28,180 --> 00:25:30,900
So, it's 30% bigger than a Typhoon-class sub.

418
00:25:31,520 --> 00:25:34,240
The thing closes two kilometers in 25 seconds.

419
00:25:34,360 --> 00:25:39,100
This gives you a crazy acceleration, right, underwater.

420
00:25:39,220 --> 00:25:41,740
The top speed is something like 3,500 miles an hour.

421
00:25:41,740 --> 00:25:56,880
And you've got to clear a 150-foot diameter, two-kilometer-long cylinder of water out of the way to move this thing in 25 seconds.

422
00:25:57,620 --> 00:25:58,700
That water had to go somewhere.

423
00:25:58,800 --> 00:25:59,800
Water is not compressible.

424
00:26:00,240 --> 00:26:02,860
So, you would have had waves coming up.

425
00:26:03,480 --> 00:26:04,660
That did not happen.

426
00:26:04,660 --> 00:26:08,480
So, the thing is acting like it's not even interacting with the water.

427
00:26:09,860 --> 00:26:18,460
Yet, we have sonar records from this, which means sonar works by water molecules banging on things, right, and bouncing off.

428
00:26:19,320 --> 00:26:25,560
So, the water molecules are bouncing off this thing, but it's not interacting with the water all at the same time.

429
00:26:26,680 --> 00:26:29,800
How this works, I have no explanation for this.

430
00:26:30,340 --> 00:26:31,460
But that's the data.

431
00:26:31,980 --> 00:26:32,860
Now, what do you do?

432
00:26:32,860 --> 00:26:35,940
So, it's really perplexing.

433
00:26:36,040 --> 00:26:38,280
These things are really not simple.

434
00:26:38,540 --> 00:26:38,820
Yeah.

435
00:26:39,120 --> 00:26:42,400
Do you think you've ever studied UFO parts?

436
00:26:45,120 --> 00:26:51,060
My colleague, Matthew Shidalgas, has been working on studying debris from purported crashes.

437
00:26:51,420 --> 00:26:51,680
Really?

438
00:26:52,060 --> 00:26:52,360
Yeah.

439
00:26:52,440 --> 00:26:59,660
He has a new technique for detecting isotopes using neutron activation.

440
00:26:59,660 --> 00:27:04,320
So, he's developed this technique, and he's been working on this furiously for the last couple months.

441
00:27:04,420 --> 00:27:05,340
Neutron activations.

442
00:27:05,420 --> 00:27:07,460
How is that different than mass spec?

443
00:27:08,340 --> 00:27:22,640
Mass spec, you basically, you, typically you dissolve the material in nitric acid, and then you spray it into a, into a, some electric plates that basically electrify it, ionize it.

444
00:27:22,640 --> 00:27:29,080
And then you shoot it into a magnetic field, that constant magnetic field, the thing will move in a circle.

445
00:27:29,280 --> 00:27:31,680
So, and the radius of the circle depends on the mass.

446
00:27:31,740 --> 00:27:36,160
So, then it hits a screen depending on where the mass is, changes where it hits the screen.

447
00:27:36,160 --> 00:27:39,440
So, you can measure the mass of the isotopes inside that spray.

448
00:27:39,760 --> 00:27:46,620
And to back up for the audience, isotope differences are neutron differences in various elements.

449
00:27:46,760 --> 00:27:46,980
Right.

450
00:27:47,100 --> 00:28:00,920
And if you were to find some, you know, isotope ratios in a material that don't occur naturally on Earth and don't pattern match to asteroids, that would be this really exciting, you know, possible smoking gun that the thing is actually a UFO.

451
00:28:01,320 --> 00:28:01,580
Right.

452
00:28:01,680 --> 00:28:02,040
Exactly.

453
00:28:02,160 --> 00:28:02,560
Well said.

454
00:28:03,060 --> 00:28:03,600
Thank you.

455
00:28:03,680 --> 00:28:04,580
Summarized that very nicely.

456
00:28:04,580 --> 00:28:06,360
Yeah, that's exactly it.

457
00:28:06,360 --> 00:28:09,020
And so, Matthew's technique is different.

